T1  - Impact of “Adverse Selection” on Managers' Project Evaluation Decisions
AU  - Harrison, Paul D.
AU  - Harrell, Adrian
Y1  - 1993/06/01
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256596
DO  - 10.5465/256596
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 635
EP  - 643
VL  - 36
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Agency theory can be used to explain decisions to continue a failing project. The results of a decision-making experiment provide empirical support for the proposition that when the conditions for adverse selection exist?an agent has private information and an incentive to shirk?such decisions, apparently irrational from a principal's perspective, may be rational from the agent's perspective.
AB  - Agency theory can be used to explain decisions to continue a failing project. The results of a decision-making experiment provide empirical support for the proposition that when the conditions for adverse selection exist?an agent has private information and an incentive to shirk?such decisions, apparently irrational from a principal's perspective, may be rational from the agent's perspective.
