TY  - JOUR
T1  - Some Organizational Consequences of Ceo Succession
AU  - Miller, Danny
Y1  - 1993/06/01
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256597
DO  - 10.5465/256597
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 644
EP  - 659
VL  - 36
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This longitudinal study examined the impact that chief executive officer succession had on changes in the structures and strategy-making processes of some large corporations. The results indicate that succession events tended to be followed by a diffusion of authority and, in the context of poor performance, by increased organizational information processing. New leadership was also associated with change, regardless of direction, in most of the dimensions of structure and process assessed.
AB  - This longitudinal study examined the impact that chief executive officer succession had on changes in the structures and strategy-making processes of some large corporations. The results indicate that succession events tended to be followed by a diffusion of authority and, in the context of poor performance, by increased organizational information processing. New leadership was also associated with change, regardless of direction, in most of the dimensions of structure and process assessed.
